<DOC><DOCNO> AP880824-0181 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2052EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BRF--GeneticFlower     08-24 0152</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Genetic Flower,140</SECOND><HEAD>Genetic Research Produces New Flower</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Commercial flower growers will have a new,genetically engineered dwarf version of the long-stemmed lisianthusby next spring, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.   Roger H. Lawson of the department's Agricultural ResearchService said the deep-purple lisianthus may be the first commercialflower developed through biotechnology research.   he dwarf lisianthus will be sold as potted plants, rather thanseed, and will be available in April 1989, he said. It will be madeavailable by the Society of American Florists and USDA.   Lawson, who heads up a new floral crops program funded jointlyby USDA and the floral society, said the new plant bears severaltulip-sized blooms at once, is a 6- to 10-inch mutation of a2-foot-tall lisianthus that is popular in many parts of the worldas a cut flower.   Wild lisianthus grows throughout the American prairie region, hesaid.</TEXT></DOC>